<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="50" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,790,283,310]" box="[264,790,283,310]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">
<heading bold="true" box="[264,790,283,310]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,790,283,310]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">
The 
<taxonomicName box="[320,614,284,310]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavoscutellata">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[320,614,284,310]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">Pegomya flavoscutellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1324,359,865]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">
In this species group, which equals the ‘ 
<taxonomicName box="[731,1020,359,384]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavoscutellata">
<emphasis box="[731,1020,359,384]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">Pegomya flavoscutellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
superspecies’ of 
<bibRefCitation author="Griffiths" pageId="1" pageNumber="54" refString="Griffiths, G. C. D. (1984) Anthomyiidae [part]. In: Griffiths, G. C. D. (Ed.), Flies of the Nearctic Region, 8 (2), 3. E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart, pp. 289 - 408. Michelsen, V. (1976) Scatophagidae, Anthomyiidae, Fanniidae og Muscidae fra Anholt (Diptera, Muscoidea). Flora og Fauna, 82, 71 - 78." type="journal article" year="1984">
Griffiths (
<number box="[273,336,399,425]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="1984.0">1984</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, I recognize three species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Zetterstedt, 1838" authorityName="Zetterstedt" authorityYear="1838" box="[672,1108,399,425]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavoscutellata">
<emphasis box="[672,876,399,424]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">P. flavoscutellata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Zetterstedt" box="[893,1099,399,425]" pageId="1" pageNumber="55" refString="Zetterstedt, J. W. (1838) Sectio tertia. Diptera. In: Insecta Lapponica. Lipsiae (' 1840 '), pp. 477 - 868." type="journal article" year="1838">
Zetterstedt, 
<number box="[1037,1099,399,425]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="1838.0">1838</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Griffiths, 1984" authorityName="Griffiths" authorityYear="1984" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flaviantennata">
<emphasis box="[1122,1322,399,424]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">P. flaviantennata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Griffiths" box="[264,441,439,465]" pageId="1" pageNumber="54" refString="Griffiths, G. C. D. (1984) Anthomyiidae [part]. In: Griffiths, G. C. D. (Ed.), Flies of the Nearctic Region, 8 (2), 3. E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart, pp. 289 - 408. Michelsen, V. (1976) Scatophagidae, Anthomyiidae, Fanniidae og Muscidae fra Anholt (Diptera, Muscoidea). Flora og Fauna, 82, 71 - 78." type="journal article" year="1984">
Griffiths, 
<number box="[382,441,439,465]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="1984.0">1984</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[505,677,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curviphallis" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[505,677,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">P. curviphallis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[695,842,439,465]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
. The group is defined primarily by one strong synapomorphy, the characteristically sickle­shaped male distiphallus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="50" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1324,359,865]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">
Only colour and minor morphological differences distinguish species of the 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavoscutellata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">P. flavoscutellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. 
<taxonomicName box="[625,917,559,584]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavoscutellata">
<emphasis box="[625,917,559,584]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">Pegomya flavoscutellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a widespread Holarctic species (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Michelsen" box="[324,521,599,625]" pageId="1" pageNumber="55" refString="Michelsen, V. (2004) Anthomyiidae. In: Pape, T. (Ed.), Diptera Brachycera. Fauna Europaea version 1.1. Available from http: // www. faunaeur. org (last accessed June 2006)." type="book chapter" year="2004">
Michelsen 
<number box="[459,521,599,625]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Griffiths" box="[538,714,599,625]" pageId="1" pageNumber="54" refString="Griffiths, G. C. D. (1984) Anthomyiidae [part]. In: Griffiths, G. C. D. (Ed.), Flies of the Nearctic Region, 8 (2), 3. E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart, pp. 289 - 408. Michelsen, V. (1976) Scatophagidae, Anthomyiidae, Fanniidae og Muscidae fra Anholt (Diptera, Muscoidea). Flora og Fauna, 82, 71 - 78." type="journal article" year="1984">
Griffiths 
<number box="[652,714,599,625]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="1984.0">1984</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Fan" box="[731,850,599,625]" pageId="1" pageNumber="54" refString="Fan, Z. (Ed.) (1988) Diptera: Anthomyiidae. Economic insect fauna of China, 37. Science Press, Beijing, 396 pp, 10 pls." type="book" year="1988">
Fan 
<number box="[788,850,599,625]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="1988.0">1988</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), which is locally abundant. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flaviantennata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">Pegomya flaviantennata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Griffiths" box="[604,793,639,665]" pageId="1" pageNumber="54" refString="Griffiths, G. C. D. (1984) Anthomyiidae [part]. In: Griffiths, G. C. D. (Ed.), Flies of the Nearctic Region, 8 (2), 3. E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart, pp. 289 - 408. Michelsen, V. (1976) Scatophagidae, Anthomyiidae, Fanniidae og Muscidae fra Anholt (Diptera, Muscoidea). Flora og Fauna, 82, 71 - 78." type="journal article" year="1984">
Griffiths (
<number box="[721,785,639,665]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="1984.0">1984</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, is morphologically almost indistinguishable from 
<taxonomicName box="[331,533,679,704]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavoscutellata">
<emphasis box="[331,533,679,704]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">P. flavoscutellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but rather differently coloured. It occurs locally in eastern North 
<collectingCountry box="[264,368,719,745]" name="United States of America" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">America</collectingCountry>
, where its range overlaps with that of 
<taxonomicName box="[832,1034,719,744]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavoscutellata">
<emphasis box="[832,1034,719,744]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">P. flavoscutellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The third taxon of this species group is 
<taxonomicName box="[465,636,759,784]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curviphallis">
<emphasis box="[465,636,759,784]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">P. curviphallis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a new species from northern Europe. It also stands very close to 
<taxonomicName box="[362,562,799,824]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavoscutellata">
<emphasis box="[362,562,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">P. flavoscutellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, both in colour and morphology, but deviates significantly in the shape of the male distiphallus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1324,918,1905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,409,918,944]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">Description</emphasis>
. The following combination of characters should enable recognition of both sexes of the 
<taxonomicName box="[410,612,959,984]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavoscutellata">
<emphasis box="[410,612,959,984]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">P. flavoscutellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group from other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1042,1151,959,984]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1042,1151,959,984]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">Pegomya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
:
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1324,918,1905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">
Medium­sized, wing length 
<quantity box="[652,801,999,1025]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="3.7" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" unit="mm" value="4.6" valueMax="5.5" valueMin="3.7">3.7–5.5 mm</quantity>
. Colour: Antennal scape, pedicel and basal part of postpedicel orange­yellow. Palpus entirely yellow. Setation on lower part of head all dark coloured. Legs yellow with brownish yellow tarsi, often blackish infuscated posteriorly on fore femur and narrowly at tips of mid and hind femora. Head: Female frons in general with well­developed pair of interfrontal setae; only 
<number box="[994,1009,1159,1185]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="2.0">2</number>
pairs of orbital setae, both reclinate. Genal setae arranged in single row. Thorax: Distance between rows of acrostichal setae equals distance between acrostichal and dorsocentral rows, except wider apart at neck region and here with some setulae between acrostichal rows. Prealar seta shorter than posterior notopleural seta. Wings: Vein C bare dorsally. Calyptrae subequal in size, lower calypter thus slightly projecting behind upper calypter, especially in males. Legs: hind tibia with 
<number box="[515,530,1399,1425]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="2.0">2</number>
<emphasis box="[537,566,1399,1424]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">ad</emphasis>
and 
<number box="[623,638,1399,1425]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="2.0">2</number>
<emphasis box="[645,674,1399,1424]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">pd</emphasis>
setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1324,918,1905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">
Male abdomen: Parallel­sided, dorso­ventrally depressed, barely expanded caudally; tergite VI bare. Sternite V (
<figureCitation box="[592,661,1479,1505]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1609,1633]" captionTargetBox="[305,1316,318,1568]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[275,1324,298,1596]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Pegomya curviphallis sp. nov., male. 1. Sternite V. 2. Hypopygium, caudal. 3. Hypopygium, lateral. 4. Pregonite. 5. Postgonite. Scale = 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173101/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">
Fig. 
<number box="[648,661,1479,1505]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
) unremarkable. Surstyli (
<figureCitation box="[967,1080,1479,1505]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1609,1633]" captionTargetBox="[305,1316,318,1568]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[275,1324,298,1596]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Pegomya curviphallis sp. nov., male. 1. Sternite V. 2. Hypopygium, caudal. 3. Hypopygium, lateral. 4. Pregonite. 5. Postgonite. Scale = 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173101/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">
Figs. 
<number box="[1035,1080,1479,1505]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3</number>
</figureCitation>
) distally obtuse and furrowed, apical incision very tight. Pregonite (
<figureCitation box="[841,915,1519,1545]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1609,1633]" captionTargetBox="[305,1316,318,1568]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[275,1324,298,1596]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Pegomya curviphallis sp. nov., male. 1. Sternite V. 2. Hypopygium, caudal. 3. Hypopygium, lateral. 4. Pregonite. 5. Postgonite. Scale = 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173101/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">
Fig. 
<number box="[899,915,1519,1545]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
) broad with one setula on top of anterior process and two very close­set setae on posterior prominence; postgonite (
<figureCitation box="[1240,1311,1559,1585]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1609,1633]" captionTargetBox="[305,1316,318,1568]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[275,1324,298,1596]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Pegomya curviphallis sp. nov., male. 1. Sternite V. 2. Hypopygium, caudal. 3. Hypopygium, lateral. 4. Pregonite. 5. Postgonite. Scale = 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173101/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">
Fig. 
<number box="[1296,1311,1559,1585]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
) with one setula on distal third. Distiphallus (
<figureCitation box="[800,914,1599,1625]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 7" captionStartId="4.[264,382,781,805]" captionTargetBox="[313,1281,317,780]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[308,1283,301,795]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 7. Pegomya spp., male, phallus. 6. P. curviphallis sp. nov. 7. P. flavoscutellata (Zetterstedt). Scale = 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173102/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">
Figs. 
<number box="[869,914,1599,1625]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="6.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="6.0">6–7</number>
</figureCitation>
) slender, characteristically sickleshaped, serrated on paraphallic processes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1324,918,1905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">
Female abdomen: Oviscapt (
<figureCitation box="[674,794,1679,1705]" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 9" captionStartId="5.[264,383,1478,1502]" captionTargetBox="[283,1305,360,1451]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[281,1306,326,1454]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 9. Pegomya curviphallis sp. nov., female: 8. Oviscapt, flat mounted. 9. Oviscapt, distal part. Scales = 0.5 mm (8); 0.25 mm (9)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173103/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="50">
Figs. 
<number box="[748,794,1679,1705]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="8.5" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="8.0">8–9</number>
</figureCitation>
) thick basally, but very slender distal to segment VII; tergite and sternite VI large, extensively pruinose and abundantly setose; tergite and sternite VII abundantly but finely setose; tergite and sternite VIII with strongly reduced setosity; epiproct strongly attenuate, with 
<number box="[889,899,1799,1825]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="1.0">1</number>
(– 
<number box="[927,943,1799,1825]" pageId="1" pageNumber="50" value="2.0">2</number>
) pairs of fine setae; hypoproct slender, smooth, with a pair of apical setulae; cerci slender, somewhat depressed, with freely projecting apices very reduced and bearing short setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
